22 yo guy who‚Äôs been dealing with it for the past couple years. It really sucks feeling alone it it and like it‚Äôs a problem that we shouldn‚Äôt have. No one picks up on behaviors or cries for help because they don‚Äôt expect to see it in a guy. Makes it really easy for the Ed to work and grow without notice. Kinda scary tbh. Over the recent years I have noticed and heard about more guys with disordered eating who don‚Äôt believe they have a problem or don‚Äôt feel justified in having one, but still have yet to meet another guy with a diagnosed disorder too. I never know what to say to them or how to help considering I‚Äôm probably not one to give advice. But it is bittersweet knowing I‚Äôm not alone in this. Just sucks to know others are going through it. I‚Äôm glad it‚Äôs being more acceptable for guys to speak up about it now and feel more validated. Subs and posts like this honestly help a lot.

I tried to share and open up about my ED with two of my ex SOs, something I regret both times. Especially with my most recent girlfriend, which my ED is actually kinda the reason we broke up. Granted I‚Äôm probably not in a solid mental state to be having a serious relationship, considering I‚Äôm already in one with my ED, so I guess it was for the best. But the time between me opening up to her until us breaking up a couple months later was pretty shitty. It could‚Äôve been due to her personality, considering everyone is different, but she ended up almost obsessing over it out of concern. I constantly felt micromanaged and watched in my daily life. Whenever I tried to open up to hear about what was happening or what I was thinking that day, she just became more upset and concerned, and it felt like I was just making her mental state worse. Again, this is probably different between people, so I think it really just depends on how you handle it and what type of person your SO is. It‚Äôs a very thin line of what to tell them and what to leave just for therapy and quite a hard one to walk at that. Hopefully if you educate them and set realistic boundaries it‚Äôll be more successful. Unfortunately I don‚Äôt think I will choose to share it again until I‚Äôm in recovery fully, just not worth the risk. Then again I guess I shouldn‚Äôt be in a relationship at this mental state. Sorry for the rambling and vent lol just getting some thoughts down I guess. Hopefully it helps

I relate to this a lot. I am not one to talk about any of my problems or share it with people. Even SO typically. Unfortunately I decided to try and break that habit with my past two girlfriends and be open with them, which did not turn out well. 

Honestly, I‚Äôm all for being open in a relationship and such. I think in a real and true relationship, you should be able to share and be open about struggles and issues. To have a support system that includes a SO I‚Äôm sure is great(I wouldn‚Äôt know lol). My experience in the matter hasn‚Äôt been great. Both of my SO I tried to share with and be open to about my problems with, did not take it well. They both ended up blaming relationship problems on my ED, getting angry at me for the behaviors my ED caused, and consistently tried to micromanage me (such as getting angry with me if I missed a meal). Im not sure why they both did those things, but my guess is that they were not used to dealing with mental illness and did not know how to act, even though I tried to help them understand. I‚Äôm sure having the right person can be very helpful when recovering and battling an ED, but I have resolved not to tell any future SOs or even try and date while I‚Äôm dealing with this shit. It‚Äôs like having two different relationships competing for my time haha. Obviously I probably shouldn‚Äôt be giving relationship advice, but hopefully my thoughts give some help as to things to look out for I guess. Best of luck, hopefully you can do better than I have.
